passages.text: Despite index level spreads hovering near all- time tights, dispersion in the HY market remains stubbornly high. Will this gap resolve through broader index widening, or through compression of the left tail? We think the status quo will persist, leaving alpha generation squarely at the single- name level. Relief from the Fed is also largely priced, meaning a further rate rally would likely come from a downward growth shock which would pressure vulnerable margins in the distressed universe.

There have been tangible signs of differentiation between sovereign and corporate risks, with a growing list of French bonds that trade tighter than similar maturity OATs. That said, French issuers have begun to underperform their Spanish and Italian peers, especially among financials. We think these relative valuation gaps will likely persist.

The narrowing yield gap between the leveraged loan and HY bond markets has balanced volumes of bond- for- loan and loan- for- bond takeouts this year, a trend we think will remain in place even after the Fed starts delivering cuts. We also continue to think Fed cuts are unlikely to trigger a meaningful rotation out of money markets funds, as the value proposition of cash as an asset class is unlikely to fully dissipate.

A likely new normal for HY dispersion. The persistently high level of dispersion in the USD and EUR HY markets remains a central theme in our conversations with investors. As we have discussed on numerous occasions, this elevated dispersion largely reflects the enduring relative valuation gap among lower- quality issuers. As shown in Exhibit 1, the spread ratio between the average and median bond in both the USD and EUR HY indices is now above the \(85^{\text{th}}\) percentile over the past 10 years, demonstrating that, while half of the index, which is BB- rated, has again reverted to February tights, the more distressed segment of the HY market has not seen similar relief (Exhibit 1). This backdrop raises a central question for investors: will this gap resolve through broader index widening, or through compression of the left tail? In other words, will there be another leg of spread compression that would warrant an overweight allocation on the CCC bucket, or should investors continue to lean into selective opportunities in the CCC bucket. We expect a status quo environment—where the relative valuation gap persists—leaving alpha generation squarely at the single- name level. We continue to recommend an underweight allocation on the CCC bucket given the current sluggish growth environment, the secular challenges facing many issuers, and the limited scope for any further relief in funding costs. We also reiterate our overweight allocation on the B bucket in both the USD and EUR markets.
Exhibit 1: A stubborn left tail of HY has dragged the average bond much wider than the median HY spread ratio of average bond-level OAS relative to median bond OAS
Source: iBoxx, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

- A closer look at the stubborn left tail of HY. The primary reason to remain selective on the CCC bucket is the heavy issuer concentration. To put things in context, 101 issuers fall in the top decile of the USD HY index constituents ranked by spread level but only 10 issuers account for \(38\%\) of the total par value of the bonds outstanding. Unsurprisingly, the 10 largest issuers in this decile screen poorly on fundamentals with a median net leverage ratio of \(7.9x\) while five of the ten have negative interest coverage ratios and only two have ratios above one. The same pattern is visible in the EUR HY index. The top decile encompasses 46 out of 383 issuers in the index but the top 10 issuers account for \(44\%\) of the total par value. Similarly, sector concentration is high in the USD HY market, as a third of the widest decile issuers come from the TMT sector which continues to grapple with multiple secular challenges—from muted customer demand and an increasingly fragmented competitive landscape, to high capital intensity and the constant threat of technological disruption—at a time when funding costs

remain elevated (Exhibit 2). While the left tail of the EUR HY index has a more balanced sector mix, it still exhibits a heavy tilt towards cyclical industries across Consumer, Basic Materials and Real Estate (Exhibit 2). The concentration validates our continued caution around cyclical risk in the USD HY market and our view that allocations to the distressed segment of HY should be predicated on credit selection, not a macro tailwind.

Exhibit 2: The sector composition of the widest scale of HY favors cyclical sectors like TMT and consumer names Sector composition of issuers which account for the widest 10 percent of bonds in the USD (left panel) and EUR (right panel) HY indices
Source: Bloomberg, iBoxx, Goldman Sachs Global Investment

Fed cuts are unlikely to help given how much is in the price already. The relative bifurcation in the USD and EUR HY markets has meant that CCCs are now trading at close to their widest relative to the broader index (Exhibit 3). Yet despite the ratio above the \(90^{\text{th}}\) percentile, outright CCC spreads are at the \(28^{\text{th}}\) percentile in both markets since 2000 (again, Exhibit 3), meaning the scope for some convergence requires a positive catalyst for the distressed segments. Following the weak July employment report and Chair Powell's Jackson Hole speech, many market participants have begun looking to the September FOMC as the beginning of a cutting cycle that could bring these names tighter. The logic would require relief to the economics of refinancing which, as we have noted before, remains difficult for CCCs with current yields sitting 250bps above maturing coupon levels. The bar for Fed cuts to bring down term yields is also quite high, in our view. With the market pricing over two cuts through this year, and over 130bps of cuts through 2026, the scope for relief relative to our economists' baseline of three cuts through year- end and 125bps through next year is de minimis. Said differently, the relief from the Fed is already priced, meaning a further rate rally would be more likely to come from a downward growth shock which would spell trouble for vulnerable margins in the distressed universe.
Exhibit 3: CCCs are trading close historically wide relative to the rest of the HY complex, but are not cheap historically
Source: Bloomberg,ICE-BAML,Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

France: Absolute underperformance may not retest past lows, but relative underperformance will. The scheduled September 8 confidence vote is a fresh reminder that French political risk and budget concerns remain an overhang. While OAT volatility was milder this week than in last December, the cumulative effect is showing up in relative pricing. Five- year OAT yields now trade higher than BTPs despite France's rating of AA- (negative outlook) vs. Italy's modal BBB rating, underscoring a persistent sovereign risk premium. Further, roughly 9 French issuers with 21 bonds outstanding now trade tighter than similar maturity OATs (about \(4\%\) of the French IG universe), and a record number of EUR IG bonds and issuers are now enjoying lower borrowing costs than the French government (Exhibit 4). Even so, the sovereign overhang is weighing on the relative spread performance of French issuers. As Exhibit 5 shows, French corporate issuers have underperformed their Italian and Spanish peers of similar ratings in recent years, with the effect being more pronounced among financials, which now trade wider than similarly rated Italian and Spanish financials. This pattern validates the findings of our previous research: in periods of elevated sovereign stress, financials tend to lag given their higher exposure to sovereign dynamics. Our economists and rates strategists expect this episode of French political turmoil to be more benign than prior flare- ups and do not anticipate new elections or a material widening of OAT- Bund spreads. Nonetheless, the persistence of French political uncertainty argues for continued relative pressure on French corporates, especially financials.

Exhibit 4: A record number of French and EUR IG corporate bonds now trade inside OATs Number of non-financial issuers (left panel) and bonds (right panel) that yield less than OATs of a similar maturity
Source: iBoxx, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
Exhibit 5: French corporate spreads have underperformed Italian and Spanish corporates in recent years French vs. Italian and Spanish corporate spread differentials duration and rating matched
Source: Bloomberg, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Issuer migration between the loan and bond markets will likely remain balanced. In early 2022, just before the Fed embarked on its hiking cycle, the yield differential between HY bonds and leveraged loans reached near all- time high levels with equivalently rated HY bonds yielding more than \(2\%\) over their leverage loan peers (Exhibit 6). This boosted volumes of loan- for- bond takeouts significantly as shown in Exhibit 7. In 2023 and 2024, as the yield curve inversion led to loans yielding more than their HY bond counterparts this dynamic flipped with bond- for- loan takeouts far outpacing loan- for- bond deals. So far in 2025, takeouts between the two markets have been on a roughly similar pace, as the yield differential between the two markets has trended back toward zero. On our estimates there have been 23 institutional bond- for- loan takeout deals this year worth \(\) 16.4\(billion versus 16 institutional loan - for - bond transactions worth\) \ \(15.1\) billion. With our US economists expecting 125bp of Fed cuts over the next nine months even while our rates strategists expect term

interest rates to remain in their current neighborhood, we anticipate the yield differential between HY bonds and leveraged loans should come back into positive territory and likely fuel another leg of loan-for-bond takeout transactions.

Source: Pitchbook LCD, ICE-BAML, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

The great (non)rotation out of money market funds. The prospect of Fed cuts has also reignited the debate around the potential for a large rotation out of money markets funds. From March 2022 to August 2024, as the Fed hiked the Fed Funds rate and maintained it at elevated levels, assets under management in USD money market funds grew from \(4.6 trillion to\) 6.3 trillion. The strong inflows into money market funds largely reflected the return of cash as an attractive value proposition for asset allocators and portfolio managers. But even after the Fed embarked on cutting the Funds rate last year, AUM in money market funds has continued to grow now reaching \(7.1 trillion as of the end of July. When it comes to the impact of normalization cuts on flows, the historical evidence is rather mixed. Exhibit 8 plots the 12-month trailing cumulative net flows as a percentage of AUM into money markets funds vs. the level of the Fed funds rate going back to the mid-1980s. The two episodes that most resemble the upcoming adjustment cuts, 1995 and 2019, did not cause any large rotation out of money market funds.
Exhibit 8: In both 1995 and 2019, the Fed's 'adjustment cuts' did not cause a large rotation out of money market funds
Source: ICI, Haver Analytics, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

September seasonality: A modest headwind for EUR credit. Strong summer technicals have supported spreads across the USD and EUR market, but September has historically brought a meaningful pickup in net supply in the EUR IG and HY markets and some widening in spreads. As shown in Exhibits 9 and 10, the median September net issuance over the past decade is notably higher in EUR than in USD, and the median monthly spread performance points to spreads widening in EUR IG and HY in September, whereas USD markets have been more muted. This year's net supply has not followed the usual seasonal script—EUR HY net supply was negative in Q1 when it's typically positive, and issuance was stronger than usual from May to July—largely reflecting headline volatility (tariffs and related uncertainty) that impacted pricing and issuance behavior. With a material portion of that volatility now behind us following the US- EU trade deal, we think seasonal patterns could resume. We therefore expect a September uptick in EUR supply and a modest headwind for spreads, while seasonality in USD remains less pronounced, particularly for IG.
Exhibit 9: Net issuance tends to increase in September for the EUR IG, EUR HY and USD HY market
Source:Bloomberg,Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
Exhibit 10: EUR IG and HY spreads tend to widen in September whereas USD IG and HY spreads are roughly unchanged
Source:Bloomberg,Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
A near-record H1 for foreign participation in the USD market. We have long argued that the bar for outright foreign selling of USD credit is high and the path of least

resistance for foreign purchasers facing currency headwinds from unhedged positions would lie elsewhere. June's TIC data for foreign purchases punctuates a strong end to the first half of the year where these worries failed to materialize, as the \(34 billion in net foreign purchases have taken year- to- date net purchases of USD corporates to\) 186 billion, the largest first- half total since 2015 and second largest since the data's 2012 inception (Exhibit 11). Also of note was that no broad region was a net seller of USD corporates over the first half of the year, validating the broad- based demand for what are still attractive all- in yields on corporate debt. Put differently, the continued strong purchase data shows that foreign investors can and likely will disentangle the currency from the asset.

Source: Department of Treasury, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
